{{Multiple issues| {{refimprove|date=March 2009}} {{more footnotes|date=March 2009}} }}
'''Political cinema''' in the narrow sense of the term is a cinema which portrays current or historical events or social conditions in a partisan way in order to inform or to agitate the spectator.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Political cinema exists in different forms such as [[documentary film|documentaries]], feature films, or even animated and [[experimental film]]s.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
==Notion== Political cinema in the narrow sense of the term refers to political films which do not hide their political stance. This does not mean that they are necessarily pure [[propaganda]]. The difference to other films is not that they are political but how they show it.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
Even ostensibly "apolitical" escapist films, which promise "mere entertainment" as an escape from everyday life, however, fulfill a political function. The authorities in Nazi Germany knew this very well and organized a large production of deliberately escapist movies.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
In other entertainment movies, for example [[western (genre)|western]]s, the ideological bias is evident in the distortion of historical reality. A "classical" western would rarely portray black cowboys, although there were a great many of them. Hollywood Cinema or more generally speaking so called [[Dominant Cinema]], was often accused of misrepresenting black, women, gays and working-class people.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
More fundamentally not only the content of individual films is political but also the [[institution]] of cinema itself. A huge number of people congregate not to act together or to talk to each other but, after having paid for it, to sit silently, to be spectators separated from each other. (Of course the behaviour of the public is not always the same in all countries.) [[Guy Debord]], a critic of the society of the spectacle, for whom "separation is the alpha and omega of the spectacle" was therefore also violently opposed to Cinema, even though he would make several movies portraying his ideas.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
==Cinema, World War I and its aftermath== Before World War I French cinema had a big share of the world market. Hollywood used the collapse of the French production to establish its [[hegemony]]. Ever since it has dominated world film production not only economically but has transformed cinema into a means to disseminate American values.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
In Germany the [[Universum Film AG]], better known as UFA, was founded to counter the perceived dominance of western propaganda. During the Weimar Republic many films about [[Frederick II of Prussia]] had a conservative nationalistic agenda, as [[Siegfried Kracauer]] and other film critics noted.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
Communists like [[Willi Münzenberg]] saw the Russian cinema as a model of political cinema. Soviet films by [[Sergei Eisenstein]], [[Dziga Vertov]] and others combined a partisan view of the bolshevist regime with artistic innovation which also appealed to western audiences.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
==Film and National Socialism== [[Leni Riefenstahl]] has never been able or willing to face her responsibility as a chief propagandist for National Socialism. Almost unlimited resources and her undeniable talent led to results which despite their hideous aims still fascinate some film aficionados. There is much controversy around her work, but it is generally accepted that Riefenstahl's main commitment was to moviemaking, rather than to the Nazi party. Proof of that might be seen by the portrayal of [[Jesse Owens]]' victory on the movie ''[[Olympia (1938 film)|Olympia]]'' (about the Olympic games in [[Germany]]) and in her later work, mostly on her photographic expeditions to Africa.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
The same is certainly not true of the violently antisemite films of Fritz Hippler. Other Nazi political films made propaganda for so-called [[euthanasia]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
==Forms== Form has always been an important concern for political film makers. While some, like pioneering [[Lionel Rogosin]], argued that radical films, in order to liberate the imagination of the spectator, have to break not only with the content but also with the form of Dominant cinema, the falsely reassuring clichés and stereotypes of conventional narrative film making, other directors such as [[Francesco Rosi]], [[Costa Gavras]], [[Ken Loach]], [[Oliver Stone]], [[Spike Lee]] or [[Lina Wertmüller]] preferred to work within mainstream cinema to reach a wider audience.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
The subversive tradition dates back at least to the French [[avant-garde]] of the 1920s. Even in his more conventional films [[Luis Buñuel]] stuck to the spirit of outright [[revolt]] of L'Âge d'or. The bourgeoisie had to be expropriated and all its values destroyed, the surrealists believed. This spirit of revolt is also present in all films of [[Jean Vigo]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
==Remembrance and reflection== Especially in the last decades of the twentieth century, many film makers considered focusing on remembrance of and reflection upon major collective crimes such as [[The Holocaust]], [[slavery]] and disasters such as the [[Chernobyl disaster]] to be their political and moral duty.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
==Globalization and related world issues== Political cinema of the twenty-first century seems to focus on controversial topics such as [[globalization]], [[AIDS]] and other health-care concerns, issues pertaining to the [[natural environment|environment]], such as [[world energy resources and consumption]] and [[climate change]], and other complex matters pertaining to [[terrorism]], [[war]], [[peace]], [[Religious intolerance|religious and related forms of intolerance]], and [[civil and political rights]] and other [[human rights]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}
==Selected filmography== : ''The following is a listing of notable political films or political films made by notable directors'': {{div col|colwidth=30em}} * 1915 – ''[[The Birth of a Nation]]''. Director: [[D. W. Griffith]].<ref>For detailed information, see: ''[http://www.filmsite.org/birt.html Birth of a Nation]'' at [[filmsite.org]].</ref><ref><blockquote>[[D. W. Griffith]]'s highly controversial film, which glorifies the [[Ku Klux Klan]], is widely considered to be a masterpiece because of its impact on the development of the cinema. The basic structure consists of a description of an idealized lost [[idyll]] ("the Old South"), the disruption of this order during [[Reconstruction era of the United States|reconstruction]] after the Civil War, and the restoration of [[White supremacy]], which is shown a legitimate goal that unites the former enemies. In the end the leader of the Ku Klux Klan secures his private happiness too and the alleged idyll is restored.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}<blockquote></ref> * 1924 – ''Stachka'' (Strike). Director: [[Sergei Eisenstein]], Russian. * 1925 – ''Bronenosets Potyomkin'' (''[[The Battleship Potemkin]]''). Director: [[Sergei Eisenstein]], Russian. * 1927 – ''The Fall of the Romanov Dynasty''. Director: [[Esfir Shub]]. * 1929 – ''Chelovek s kino-apparatom'' (''[[Man with a Movie Camera]]''). Director: [[Dziga Vertov]]. * 1931 – ''Mädchen in Uniform'' (''[[Girls in uniform]]''). Director: [[Leontine Sagan]]. * 1932 – ''Kuhle Wampe oder Wem gehört die Welt?'' (''[[To Whom Does the World Belong?]]''). Director: [[Slatan Dudow]]. * 1933 – ''[[Misère au Borinage]]''. Directors: [[Joris Ivens]] and [[Henri Storck]].<ref>Militant film about the misery of Belgian coal miners. [[Cf.]] ''Les Enfants du borinage: Lettre à Henri Storck'', Director: [[Patric Jean]], 2000.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1935 – ''Triumph des Willens'' (''[[Triumph of the Will]]''). Director: [[Leni Riefenstahl]], Germany.<ref>Technically brilliant propaganda film about the Reichsparteitag in [[Nuremberg]] 1934.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1940 – ''Der ewige Jude. Ein Filmbeitrag zum Weltjudentum'' (''[[The Eternal Jew (1940 film)]]''). Director: [[Fritz Hippler]].<ref>Virulently antisemitic.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1948 – ''[[Strange Victory]]''. Director: [[Leo Hurwitz]].<ref>"He creates the image of an America that is complacent in its victory, prosperity and racism; the narrator warns: 'Nigger, kike, wop, take my advice and accept the facts – the world is already arranged for you'&nbsp;" (Barsam).<!--Still needs a specific page reference.--></ref> * 1953 – ''[[Salt of the Earth (1954 film)|Salt of the Earth]]''. Director: [[Herbert Biberman]].<ref>Legendary documentary feature film about a [[Strike action|strike]] in [[New Mexico]]. Not only do the workers have to fight against the company, but also their women against their macho attitude in order to be "allowed" to support them fully.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1954 – ''[[Ernst Thälmann]]'' (Sohn seiner Klasse. Ein Farbfilm der DEFA). Director: [[Kurt Maetzig]].<ref>[[Socialist realism]] – [[German Democratic Republic]] style.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1956 – ''[[On the Bowery]]''. Director: [[Lionel Rogosin]].<ref>An important film about [[alcoholism]]; homeless people in New York City.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1964 – ''[[The Cool World (film)|The Cool World]]''. Director: [[Shirley Clarke]].<ref>About the cruel reality of street life in the U.S.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1965 – ''Obyknovennyy fashizm'' (''[[Ordinary Fascism]]''). Director: [[Mikhail Romm]]. * 1966 – ''[[The Battle of Algiers]]. Director: [[Gillo Pontecorvo]]. * 1967 – ''[[La Chinoise]]''. Director: [[Jean-Luc Godard]]. * 1967 – ''[[Titicut Follies]]''. Director: [[Frederick Wiseman]].<ref>In his first film Wiseman shows the inhumane conditions in Bridgewater State Hospital in [[Massachusetts]]. For more than 20 years the film could not been shown in the USA.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1968 – ''La Hora de los hornos: Acto para la liberación: notas, testimonios y debate sobre las recientes luchas de liberación del pueblo argentino'' (''[[The Hour of the Furnaces]]''). Director: [[Fernando Solanas]]. * 1968 – ''[[In the Year of the Pig]]''. Director: [[Emile de Antonio]].<ref>A [[compilation film]] about the [[Vietnam War]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1968 – ''[[Teorema (film)|Teorema]]''. Director: [[Pier Paolo Pasolini]].<ref>The power of desire disrupts a rich family.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1968 – ''[[if....]]''. Director: [[Lindsay Anderson]]. * 1969 – ''[[Z (1969 film)|Z]]''. Director: [[Costa-Gavras]]. * 1969 – ''[[Yawar mallku]]'' (''Blood of the Condor''). Director: [[Jorge Sanjinés]]. * 1969 – ''[[Salesman (1969 film)|Salesman]]''. Directors/Editors: [[Albert and David Maysles]] and [[Charlotte Zwerin]].<ref>Four men try to sell the Bible; one of the most important films of [[Direct Cinema]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1970 – ''Le chagrin et la pitié'' (''[[The Sorrow and the Pity]]''). Director: [[Marcel Ophüls]].<ref>Politically a pathbreaking documentary about [[collaboration]] in [[France]] during the German occupation.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1970 – ''Warum läuft Herr R. Amok?'' (''[[Why Does Herr R. Run Amok?]]''). Director: [[Rainer Werner Fassbinder]].<ref>Concerns the humiliating madness of ordinary life.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1971 – ''Nicht der Homosexuelle ist pervers, sondern die Situation, in der er lebt'' (''[[It Is Not the Homosexual Who Is Perverse, But the Society in Which He Lives]]''). Director: [[Rosa von Praunheim]].<ref>This film started the second gay movement in Germany.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1971 – ''[[Wanda (film)|Wanda]]''. Director: [[Barbara Loden]] * 1971 – ''La classe operaia va in paradiso'' (''[[The Working Class Goes to Heaven]]''). Director: [[Elio Petri]]. * 1972 – ''Il Caso Mattei'' (''[[The Mattei Affair]]''). Director: [[Francesco Rosi]]. * 1972 – ''[[Sambizanga (film)|Sambizanga]]''. Director: [[Sarah Maldoror]].<ref>A [[feature film]] about the [[liberation movement]] in [[Angola]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1973 – ''[[La Société du spectacle (film)|La Société du spectacle]]'' (''[[The Society of the Spectacle (film)|Society of the Spectacle]]''). Director: [[Guy Debord]]. * 1974 – ''Angst essen Seele auf'' (''[[Ali: Fear Eats the Soul]]''). Director: [[Rainer Werner Fassbinder]].<ref>A poignant [[feature film]] about [[racism]], [[Human sexuality|sexuality]], [[love]] and [[ageism]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 1975 – ''[[Jeanne Dielman, 23 Quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles]]'' (''Everyday Life of a Housewife''). Director: [[Chantal Akerman]].<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=uPtuaV7IAt0C&pg=PT140 |title=Cult Cinema - Ernest Mathijs, Jamie Sexton - Google Boeken |page=140 |date=2012-03-30 |accessdate=2015-02-20}}</ref><ref>http://www.elle.fr/Loisirs/Cinema/News/Chantal-Akerman-retour-sur-la-carriere-d-une-cineaste-discrete-3002285</ref> * 1976 – ''[[Harlan County, USA]]''. Director: [[Barbara Kopple]]. * 1977 – ''[[Yarinsiz Adam]], (The Man without Tomorrow), [[Cinema of Turkey|Turkey]]. Director: [[Remzi Aydın Jöntürk]]. * 1977 – ''[[Yıkılmayan Adam]], (Indestructible Man), [[Cinema of Turkey|Turkey]]''. Director: [[Remzi Aydın Jöntürk]]. * 1978 – ''Baara'' (''Work''). Director: [[Souleymane Cissé]]. * 1978 – ''[[Yıkılmayan Adam]]'' (Indestructible Man). Director: [[Remzi Aydın Jöntürk]], [[Turkey]]. * 1981 – ''[[Reds (film)|Reds]]''. Director: [[Warren Beatty]]. * 1982 – ''[[Yol]]''. (''The Road'' or ''The Way''). Director: [[Yılmaz Güney]] and [[Şerif Gören]]. * 1984 – ''[[Before Stonewall]]''. Director: [[Greta Schiller]]. * 1986 – ''[[Shoah (film)|Shoah]]''. Director: [[Claude Lanzmann]]. * 1989 – ''[[Camp de Thiaroye]]''. Director: [[Ousmane Sembène]]. * 1991 – ''[[American Dream (film)|American Dream]]''. Director: [[Barbara Kopple]]. * 1995 – ''[[Land and Freedom]]''. Director: [[Ken Loach]]. * 2000 – ''[[Lumumba (film)|Lumumba]]''. Director: [[Raoul Peck]].<ref>A moving and very intelligent poetical reflection on the presence of apparently bygone hopes and disasters. Dubbed in English.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 2001 – ''[[Intimacy (film)|Intimacy]]''. Director: [[Patrice Chéreau]].<ref>Intense [[feature film]] on [[solitude]], alienated [[human sexuality|sexuality]], and an impossible love.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 2002 – ''[[War and Peace (2002 film)|Jang aur Aman/War and Peace]]''. Director: [[Anand Patwardhan]].<ref>On nuclear madness in [[India]] and [[Pakistan]] and their efforts to imitate Big Brother, [[United States|USA]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 2003 – ''Gujarat: A Laboratory of Hindu Rastra, Fascism''. Director: [[Suma Josson]]. * 2004 – ''Memoria del saqueo'' (Social Genocide). Director: [[Fernando Solanas]].<ref>A passionately partisan survey of the history of [[neoliberalism]] in [[Argentina]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 2004 – ''[[Darwin's Nightmare]]''. Director: [[Hubert Sauper]].<ref>Using the effect of fishing the Nile perch in Tanzania's Lake Victoria as an example, Sauper shows how [[Africa]] functions today, how famine, wars and aids, European "aid" and the ruthless plundering of African resources are connected.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 2005 – ''[[500 Years Later]]''. Director [[Owen Alik Shahadah]]<ref>An African American documentary on race and the social impact of slavery.</ref> * 2005 – ''[[Syriana]]''. Director [[George Clooney]]. * 2006 – ''[[The Road to Guantanamo]]''. Director: [[Michael Winterbottom]]. * 2006 – ''[[The Last Communist]]''. Director: [[Amir Muhammad (director)|Amir Muhammad]], [[Malaysia]].<ref>Documentary film based on the autobiography of [[Chin Peng]], born in 1924, the last chairman of the forbidden [[Communist Party of Malaya]] (CPM) but this is not a conventional biographical film. Key elements in the film are the songs Hardesh Singh composed for the occasion. This is an often funny film about a difficult chapter in Malaysian history which is still taboo "back home".{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 2006 – ''[[The Short Life of José Antonio Gutierrez]]''. Director: [[Heidi Specogna]]. * 2006 – ''[[An Inconvenient Truth]]''. Director: [[Davis Guggenheim]]. * 2007 – ''[[Persepolis (film)|Persepolis]]''. Directors: [[Marjane Satrapi]] and [[Vincent Paronnaud]].<ref>[[Animated film]] based on the [[graphic novel]] [[Persepolis (comics)|of the same name]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}</ref> * 2007 – ''Unrepentant: Kevin Annett and Canada's Genocide''. Director: [[Louie Lawless]].<ref>[http://www.hiddenfromhistory.org/ Hidden from History: The Canadian Holocaust: The Untold Story of the Aboriginal Genocide]. ''Hidden from History.org''. Accessed 4 March 2009.</ref> * 2007 – ''[[Sicko]]''. Director: [[Michael Moore]]. * 2007 – ''[[What Would Jesus Buy]]'' * 2008 – ''[[The World Without US]]''. Directors: [[Mitch Anderson (director)|Mitch Anderson]] and Jason J. Tomaric.<ref name=Amazon>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000Z961UO|title=''The World Without US'': Editorial Review|format=[[World Wide Web|Web]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=2009-03-04|quote=[This 2008 documentary film is described as] 'a quick overview of the state of the world today, and a quick history lesson in how things have been going for the last 20 years or so, followed by a few things that seem very likely to occur if America decided to pull all of its military bases out of foreign countries and stop mucking about in foreign parts.'&nbsp;}}</ref><ref name=Andersonbio>{{cite web|author=Mitch Anderson|url=http://mitchanderson.com/MitchBioShort.htm|title=Mitch Anderson's Biography|format=[[World Wide Web|Web]]|publisher=Mitch Anderson|accessdate=2009-03-04|authorlink=Mitch Anderson (director)|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615145905/http://mitchanderson.com/MitchBioShort.htm|archivedate=2008-06-15|df=}} Released in 2008, the documentary explores what might happen if the [[United States]] were to leave the international arena, rescind its global reach and become an [[United States non-interventionism|isolationist nation]] for the first time since the early 20th century.</ref><ref name=WWU>Trailer and "About the film" at {{cite web|url=http://theworldwithoutus.com/index.htm |title=The World Without US (Home Page)|format=[[World Wide Web|Web]]|accessdate=2009-03-04}}</ref> * 2008 – ''[[Religulous]]''. Director: [[Larry Charles]]. * 2008 – ''[[Milk (film)|Milk]]''. Director: [[Gus Van Sant]]. * 2009 – ''[[Capitalism: A Love Story]]'' * 2009 – ''[[American Radical: The Trials of Norman Finkelstein]]''. Directors: [[Nicolas Rossier]] & [[David Ridgen]] * 2009 – ''[[The Yes Men Fix the World]]'' * 2010 – ''[[Motherland (2010 film)|Motherland]]''. Director: [[Owen Alik Shahadah]]<ref>An African documentary on the history and contemporary state of Africa and African people.</ref> * 2011 – ''[[The Black Power Mixtape 1967–1975]]''. Director: [[Goran Olson]] * 2011 – ''[[The Ides of March (2011 film)|The Ides of March]]''. Director: George Clooney * 2011 – ''[[ToryBoy The Movie]]''. Director: [[John Walsh (filmmaker)|John Walsh]] * 2012 – ''[[2016: Obama's America]]''. Director: [[Dinesh D'Souza]] * 2014 – ''[[America: Imagine the World Without Her]]''. Director: Dinesh D'Souza * 2017 – ''[[The Death of Stalin]]''. Director: Armando Iannucci {{div col end}}
